title: Matador Cup live scores: Coverage of New South Wales v Victoria at North Sydney Oval | DailyTelegraph
text:
VICTORIA has brought New South Wales’ winning-streak to an end, beating the Blues by 21 runs in Sunday’s Matador Cup clash at North Sydney Oval.
In a game that featured 13 players that have donned the baggy green, competition leader New South Wales bowled Victoria out for 244 and at one stage was cruising at 3-159.
The Blues started their chase in impressive fashion, with Nic Maddinson hammering 20 runs off James Pattinson’s second over, hitting a six over the roof and onto a car parked outside the ground.
An over later Maddinson fell to man of the match John Hastings (4-30), trapped in front of the stumps for 20. It was the first of six straight lbws for Victoria, with Ed Cowan (39), Moises Henriques (37), Shane Watson (64), Ryan Carters (6) and Sean Abbott (0) all trapped in front of the stumps to leave the Blues on 6-172 off 37 overs.
The Blues looked like they were cruising to victory with Watson and stand-in skipper Henriques at the crease, with the pair putting on a 74-run third-wicket partnership to take the score to 3-159 when the latter fell to Hastings in the 33rd over.
Watson joined Henriques in the sheds 14 balls later and in the next over Hastings struck twice, removing Carters and Abbott.

Matthew Wade hits six out of ground 0:32 Cricket: Victoria's Matthew Wade hit Sean Abbott out of the ground at North Sydney Oval in their Matador Cup clash.
October 18th 2015 5 hours ago /video/video.news.com.au/Sport/Cricket/Highlights/ Having already secured a spot in the final, the Blues rested captain Steve Smith, but recalled Starc to a bowling attack that also featured Test stars Josh Hazlewood and Lyon.
Starc (4-58) struck in the game’s third over, clean bowling Aaron Finch (2), but he had to wait until the 45th over to get his next wicket.
Playing in his first game of the season, opener Rob Quiney scored 79 runs from 75 balls, managing to dull the new-ball attack of Starc and Hazlewood without damaging Victoria’s run rate.
For a while it looked like Quiney was going to be the only batsman to make a stand for the Vics, with Cameron White (27), Glenn Maxwell (5), Peter Handscomb (20) and Dan Christian (1) all falling before the 25th over to leave the Bushrangers at 5-122.
Quiney was the next man to go, stumped off Stephen O’Keefe (1-35), but a quickfire 63 off 65 balls from Matthew Wade ensured the Bushrangers went well past 200.
The keeper ran out of partners in the end, with Starc knocking over the last three wickets to end Victoria’s innings in the 47th over.
The left-hander has now taken at least four wickets in each of his last seven domestic one-day games and has taken 23 for the season at an average of 7.47
